<section class="ar__wrapper grid">
  <a name="section--we_dont_have_a_price"></a>
  <a href="#top" class="link--toTop">Back to top</a>

  <h1 class="grid__item one-whole">
    We don’t have a price!
  </h1>
  <p class="lead">
    This is what Sibongile Mtuki, the Deputy Principal of Thubelihle Intermediate School, who was part of a group of teachers who blew the whistle on the corruption, had to say:
  </p>

  <blockquote class="grid__item three-quarters">
    <p>
      What raised our suspicions was the fact that the same person [Ngwenya] was elected repeatedly as chairperson of the SGB. There is protocol that must be followed when choosing members of the SGB and the principal. All parents of learners are eligible for election as a member of the SGB.
    </p>
    <p>
      We decided at the last election that we did not want him [Ngwenya] back because he did not qualify to be a member of the SGB. We needed a new person with ideas and innovative thinking for the benefit of the school. Unfortunately though, he was elected once again even though he did not qualify.
    </p>
    <p>
      The situation now is that the SGB feels that we acted unfairly against the principal. They are relatively new, so I understand where they are coming from. They were not there when things started going wrong.
    </p>
    <p>
      There has been no honesty with regards to the running of the school and that looks bad in the eyes of the community. We don’t have confidence in you [Usiba]. We don’t need you.
    </p>
    <footer><cite>
     Sibongile Mtuki
    </cite></footer>
  </blockquote>

  <img src="img/sibongile.jpg" alt="Sibongile Mtuki" class="grid__item one-quarter" />
</section>

<section class="ar__wrapper grid">
  <h2 class="grid__item one-whole">
    Finding financial deceipt at Thubelihle
  </h2>

  <div class="grid__item one-half">
    <p>
      In February 2013, Corruption Watch received a complaint from a group of teachers at Thubelihle Intermediate School in White City, Soweto. It was alleged that the principal, Nonzwakazi Usiba and former chairperson of the School Governing Body (SGB), Isaac Ngwenya, were tangled in corrupt activities. It was suspected that Usiba and Ngwenya were involved in the misuse of school funds.
    </p>
    <p>
      After investigation, Corruption Watch found mass evidence of fraud in the school’s finances. We commissioned an independent auditing firm to assess our findings. The auditors confirmed that corruption was evident and that Usiba and Ngwenya were directly implicated in the wrongdoings, which included:
    </p>


    <ul>
      <li>
        41 school cheques totalling R134 487.56, made out and cashed by Usiba. Some of the cheques stated “feeding for learners” but no corresponding invoices were found.
      </li>
      <li>
        10 school cheques totalling R41 059.30 were made out to Ngwenya and no invoices corresponded with the payment.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="grid__item one-half">
    <ul>
      <li>
        Fake invoices were created for unknown individuals. For example, the school paid an amount of R48 064.74 to one individual against an invoice from Solly’s Packaging and Stationery Distributors, supposedly for calculators, pens and other stationery. It was unclear whether the stationery detailed in the fake invoice was ever delivered to the school and Solly’s Packaging told the forensic auditors that the invoice was not theirs.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      In August, Corruption Watch opened a police case against Usiba at Moroka Police Station in Soweto. The case currently sits with the Commercial Crimes Unit. Also based on findings, we approached the Gauteng Education Department (GED) and shared the forensic report with the district and provincial offices, who instituted their own investigation.
    </p>
    <p>
      The principal attempted to sidestep disciplinary processes by resigning with immediate effect. However, he was not let off the hook so easily. In this case, the GED forced him to remain in his post, though under suspension, until the investigation is complete.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

